        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Due to the compactness (diameter below 2.6") and complex structure of the source , we ask for observations in band 7 with the second most extended array configuration C34-6 (angular resolution of 0.16") and do not require the use of the ACA. We ask for Band 7 observations because this results in a higher angular resolution compared to Band 6 (key element for our science goal) and allows us to achieve the same SNR in shorter time than in Band 8, 9 and even 6 for our target. SED modeling indeed suggests that our disk is 5 times fainter in band 6, which is not compensated by the increased sensitivity. We estimate the brightness of the disk by computing simulated images based on the expected dust distribution from the available scattered light data (Fig. 1 in the attached proposal). Then we scaled them to the total flux at 870 microns measured by [3]: 19mJy. We used 5 different volumetric dust density distributions described in the "Immediate objective" section of the proposal. The parameters of these models are detailed in Table 1 and the output images and profiles are shown in Fig. 2. The worst-case scenario is found to be model 5 with a maximum flux along the semi-minor axis of 0.22 mJy/beam. We want to get an SNR of 10 at this position along the semi-minor axis in this case, in order to fulfill our science goals and constrain the steepness of the parent body distribution. This means we require a sensitivity of  0.022 mJy/beam. Using the sensitivity calculator, we find that a total integration time of 1.7 hours is sufficient to get this sensitivity, and adding up the calibration and overheads we end up with a total observing time of 4.3 hours</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
