    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>HR4796 is a young, early A-type star harboring a very bright (fractional luminosity of 0.005), well structured, debris disk, that appears in the optical/near-IR as a narrow ring at 77 AU (1") with sharp inner and outer edges. The inner edge might be shaped by a planet inside the ring, recent near-IR images (Lagrange et al 2012) allowed us constraining the possible location of this planet. The outer part of the disk is not well understood. We propose here to record the first resolved images of the disk at long wavelengths (band 7) with  ALMA data to further constrain the properties of the dust disk and determine directly, for the first time, the  location of the large-body population responsible for the dust production. The data will also allow a deep search for  gas in the system. These information will be crucial to improve the physical and dynamical modeling of the system, and provide dynamical constraints on the properties of the potential gravitational perturber(s).
</prp:abstract>
